Triage this mobile-banking crash. Use the crash-triage skill.

CRASH INPUT
- Platform: <Android | iOS>
- App version: <e.g. 5.2.1>
- Build number: <e.g. 5210>
- Stacktrace:
<paste the full stacktrace + any breadcrumbs here>

DO THIS, IN ORDER:

1. Symbolicate if the trace is obfuscated, using the matching mapping file in
   references/ for this version+build. If no symbol file exists for this build,
   say so, keep the root cause generic, lower confidence, and do NOT invent
   class/method names.

2. Redact PII (account numbers, PANs, tokens, emails) before producing any output.
   Note what was found by type and count, never the value.

3. Find the data:
   - Root cause and the responsible internal module.
   - Severity (P1/P2/P3) and affected flow.
   - Suspected file:line.
   - Primary owner = last committer of that line via git blame (label it a SUSPECT,
     not proof). Map the commit to its PR and reviewers.
   - Assignment group = the owning team.
   - A confidence score.

4. Build an HTML results page named triage_<id>.html that displays ALL of the above
   in a clean layout: a header with severity + flow, the root cause, and a table of
   owner, assignment group, suspected file, suspect PR, reviewers, PII flag, and
   confidence. Use the same dark-navy styling as the email (navy #13203B, accent
   #2D4A7C, red/amber/green only for status). Save it and open it so I can see it.

5. Write the findings to triage_result.json (matching the skill's schema, including
   owner.email and an action_url that is the GitHub create-PR link for the branch).

6. Draft the email: run
   python scripts/draft_outlook_email.py triage_result.json
   so it opens as a draft in Outlook addressed to the owner, with the
   "Review & raise draft PR" button. Do not send it — I will review and send.

GUARDRAILS: draft only, never merge. Owner is a suspect lead, not blame; never
blame the approver. Original code only. Redact PII before any output.
